&lt;h2&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s in the Syllabus! Or is it?: Designing a Transparent Syllabus (for Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 90-minute workshop for Columbia Faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;To participate in this session, all registered participants must bring or have access to a copy of their course syllabus in any stage (e.g., rough draft, revised draft, final).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The syllabus is often students&amp;rsquo; first introduction to your course, and can help set the tone for the rest of the semester, even before your first class meeting. When designed with a focus on transparency, the syllabus can signal to students that they are entering an inclusive learning space, and provide them with a clear guide of what they will learn and how they can demonstrate and monitor their learning. You will spend a majority of this interactive workshop in pairs reviewing each other&amp;rsquo;s syllabus from the student perspective.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Please note:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;In advance of this session, we ask that registered participants read the CTL&amp;rsquo;s online resource: &lt;/em&gt;&lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/resources/designing-inclusive-syllabus/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Designing an Inclusive Syllabus&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt;, which will inform the session activities. We also ask that all registered participants have their syllabus easily accessible, as there will be opportunities for collaborative workshopping throughout the session.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After attending this session, participants should be able to:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Identify overarching considerations of transparent and inclusive syllabus design&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Identify the elements of a syllabus and inclusive moves within each element&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Enact small changes to their own syllabus to revise for inclusivity and transparency&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Looking for more syllabus support? Email &lt;a href="mailto:CTLFaculty@columbia.edu"&gt;CTLFaculty@columbia.edu&lt;/a&gt; to schedule your 1-1 consultation&lt;strong&gt;. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Getting Started with Active Learning (For Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute workshop for Columbia Faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;What is active learning? Why does active learning matter? How do you actively engage your students in their learning?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this session, you will reflect on these questions and ways to move learners from passively receiving information to actively thinking about what they are learning, applying course content, and engaging with their peers. Join the session to experience active learning strategies and discuss and share your thoughts and ideas with colleagues. You will learn about and apply the Encounter-Engage-Reflect framework for building holistic active learning experiences into your course. You will leave with an initial plan for active learning in an upcoming lesson or unit in your course.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By the end of the session, participants should be able to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Select active learning strategies to meet learning objectives&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Apply the Encounter-Engage-Reflect framework for holistic active learning&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Draft a plan for one active learning experience in their course&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/resources/active-learning-basics/"&gt;Getting Started with Active Learning&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Setting Up Assignments, Quizzes, and Discussions in CourseWorks (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 30-minute session for Columbia Faculty and Graduate student instructors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Join us to learn best practices to create Assignments, Quizzes, and Discussions in CourseWorks, Columbia&amp;rsquo;s learning management system. Experience a walk through of these commonly used tools and see how CourseWorks displays graded work. You will also gain an understanding of available options and features such as giving assignments different weights, and adding extra time to quizzes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/courseworks/"&gt;Teaching with Courseworks&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Planning Your Lectures Based on the Science of Learning (for Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute session for Columbia faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;How can I plan my lectures to better help my students learn? How can I promote student engagement with course material in addition to listening to my lectures?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Come address these questions with us! We will discuss findings from the science of learning&amp;mdash;activating prior knowledge, practicing retrieval, and reflecting&amp;mdash;and simple ways you can incorporate them so students can further engage with course material. You will also have an opportunity to draft a plan for an upcoming class session and hear how your colleagues engage their learners during lectures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resources: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/teaching-online/engaged-lecturing/"&gt;Five Tips for Engaged Lecturing&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/sapp/active-learning-learner-perspective/"&gt;Active Learning: The Learner&amp;#39;s Perspective&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Engaging Students with Ed Discussion (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 30-minute demo sessions for Columbia faculty and graduate student instructors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Would you like a discussion space that encourages student-initiated discussion and fosters classroom community? Do you need a space where students can annotate each other&amp;rsquo;s images? Want an online platform where you can easily organize large numbers of posts, such as megathreads with resolvable comments?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Experience a short demonstration of &lt;a href="https://courseworks2.columbia.edu/courses/56883/pages/using-ed-discussions"&gt;Ed Discussion&lt;/a&gt;, an online discussion platform that is integrated into CourseWorks and can be used for asynchronous discussions or synchronously such as a backchannel for live in-person classes. This will be followed by opportunities to ask questions and to reflect on how you might intentionally integrate Ed Discussion into your teaching context. Note: Ed Discussion is especially useful for large courses where students are engaged in collaborative problem solving, posting equations and code, and Q&amp;amp;A exchanges.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
