&lt;h2&gt;Three Ways to Manage Your Large Course (For Faculty)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 60-minute workshop for Columbia Faculty.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;How do I engage and build community with students in my large course? How can I help my students actively engage with course materials and with each other? How can I promote academic integrity when I have so many students?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this session, you will have an opportunity to address these questions and reflect on strategies that are scalable for varying sizes of large courses. Join us in discussing ways to promote classroom community, active learning, and academic integrity to make large courses more manageable and rewarding for faculty and students alike.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unable to join us for this workshop? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/resources/teaching-large-courses/"&gt;Teaching Large Courses Effectively and Efficiently&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Engaging Students with Poll Everywhere (for Instructors)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A 30-minute demo session for Columbia Faculty and Graduate student instructors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Are you seeking a way to gauge what your students are thinking and learning in the classroom in real-time? Want to immediately display and use the results from students through in-class polling?&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Experience a short demonstration of &lt;a href="https://www.cuit.columbia.edu/live-polling"&gt;Poll Everywhere&lt;/a&gt;, an in-class polling and quizzing tool that allows you to pose various types of questions to better understand what students are learning and collect their feedback. This will be followed by opportunities to ask questions and to reflect on how you might intentionally integrate Poll Everywhere into your teaching context.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Unable to join us for this demo and Q&amp;amp;A? Engage with our on-demand resource: &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/resources-and-technology/teaching-with-technology/tech-resources/ars/"&gt;Poll Everywhere: Audience Response Systems&lt;/a&gt;. You can also schedule a &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/faculty/offerings/consultations/"&gt;consultation&lt;/a&gt;, or find other workshops on our &lt;a href="https://ctl.columbia.edu/events/"&gt;CTL events calendar&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Note: this session has been canceled. However, we welcome graduate student instructors seeking guidance on preparing for their first week of classes&amp;nbsp;to drop by the CTL&amp;#39;s office hours for graduate students Fridays, 2-4pm in room 212 Butler Library or via Zoom. Details &lt;a href="https://events.columbia.edu/cal/event/eventView.do?b=de&amp;amp;calPath=%2Fpublic%2Fcals%2FMainCal&amp;amp;guid=CAL-00bbdb71-827c8059-0182-7f59df67-00004448events@columbia.edu&amp;amp;recurrenceId=20230113T190000Z" target="_blank"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;++++&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Are you a graduate student teaching for the first time, or looking for guidance on how to prepare for your first week of classes? If you haven&amp;#39;t done so already, enroll in the Teaching Orientation for Graduate Students, organized by the Center for Teaching and Learning&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href="https://courseworks2.columbia.edu/enroll/LB6GRA" target="_blank"&gt;at this link&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;to access resources on the following topics:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Establishing instructional goals and an inclusive learning climate&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Reviewing and reflecting on&amp;nbsp;TA roles and teaching support&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Creating a policy sheet and first day of class plan&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Responding to common&amp;nbsp;TA challenges and campus resources to help navigate them&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Planning next steps for teaching and professional development&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Once you&amp;#39;ve completed these modules, we invite you to join the CTL for this optional, 60-minute,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;online&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;debrief&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;session&amp;nbsp;to discuss the&amp;nbsp;application of these ideas to your specific teaching practice and&amp;nbsp;get feedback about materials you&amp;#39;ve prepared for the first day of classes.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Completion of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://courseworks2.columbia.edu/enroll/LB6GRA" target="_blank"&gt;orientation&amp;nbsp;modules&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the drafting of a first day plan and/or policy sheet&amp;nbsp;is necessary prior to joining this session&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;in order to ensure meaningful participation in planned activities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This online session will be&amp;nbsp;facilitated via Zoom&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;by Caitlin DeClercq, Senior&amp;nbsp;Assistant Director of Graduate Student Programs and Services at the CTL.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Registrants will be emailed a Zoom link prior to the start of the session. Please note that registration closes at 11:55pm on January 11th For same-day registration, please email&amp;nbsp;CTLgrads@columbia.edu.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
