&lt;p&gt;Please join us for a discussion with &lt;strong&gt;Hannah Chazin. &lt;/strong&gt;Ancient burial monuments filled with lavish grave goods are widespread across Eurasia. Alongside glittering gold and silver cups, bronze daggers, finely-wrought jewelry, and other precious objects, many ancient graves across the region also contain &amp;lsquo;head and hoof&amp;rsquo; burials &amp;ndash; the skulls and lower limbs of horses or other livestock. While most commonly associated with the royal burials of the Scythians and shamanic practices in Siberia, there is also a long regional tradition of these burials in the South Caucasus in the Bronze Age. This talk examines the &amp;lsquo;head and hoof&amp;rsquo; burials in the Late Bronze Age South Caucasus in their local context, as part of the larger set of relations between humans and herd animals in life and in death.&amp;nbsp;Moderated by &lt;a href="https://harriman.columbia.edu/person/valentina-izmirlieva/"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Valentina Izmirlieva&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, Director of the Harriman Institute. This event is part of a&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;Director&amp;rsquo;s Seminar&lt;/strong&gt; series, which allows new Harriman faculty members to introduce their research to both colleagues and students across disciplinary and departmental divides.&lt;/p&gt;
